The Maryland coal mine industry has filed for bankruptcy that will drive up the cost of energy production for Maryland households and businesses.

The company announced on Friday that it had filed for bankruptcy bankruptcy protection in Beechfield, Md., after a last-minute agreement with the state's Office of Public Investment Finance.

Under the law, the company plans to pay $3.5 billion in debt by the end of this year.

The company had been trading at close to $6 a gallon at this week's price, up from $7 on Feb. 10, 2013, when the company was trading at $6 a gallon.

The company has been trading at $1 an ounce since Feb. 11, 2013, the same day the company said it was paying $10 an ounce for the last quarter of 2012.

The company's money has been used to pay for utility bills and other costs, including on the state's $9.5 billion debt. The $3.5 billion to compensate the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, which oversees the coal mining industry, came from the coal mine owners.

